    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nLooking at the reaction SMIRKS:\n- Reactants: [H:20][N+:21]1=C(C2=C(N=C1)N(C(=O)N2)C3C(C(C(O3)CO)O)O)NCC4=CC(=C(C(=C4)Br)O)Br.[OH-:10].[Br-]\n- Products: [H:20][OH:10].C1=C(C=C(C(=C1Br)O)Br)CNC2=[N:21]C=NC3=C2NC(=O)N3C4C(C(C(O4)CO)O)O.[Br-]\n\nThe atom mapping shows:\n- [H:20] and [N+:21] in reactants → [H:20] and [OH:10] in products (water), and [N:21] in the product molecule\n- [OH-:10] in reactants → [OH:10] in products (water)\n\nSo the key transformation is:\n1. The N+ (positively charged nitrogen, atom 21) in the reactant loses its positive charge and becomes neutral N in the product\n2. The H (atom 20) that was attached to N+ (atom 21) is transferred to OH- (atom 10) to form water (H-OH)\n3. The N+ loses H and becomes neutral N\n\nThis is a hydrolysis/deamination where a protonated amine (N+H) reacts with hydroxide to form water and a neutral amine.\n\nThe reaction center involves:\n- Bond broken: N+:21-H:20\n- Bond formed: H:20-O:10 (in water)\n- Charge change: N+:21 → N:21 (loss of positive charge)\n\nSo the reaction center is the cleavage of the N-H bond (where N is the positively charged nitrogen) and formation of O-H bond (where O is from hydroxide), producing water and neutralizing the nitrogen.\n\nLet me express this as a reaction edit summary:\n\nThe local transformation is:\n- N+:21-H:20 bond broken\n- H:20-O:10 bond formed (from OH-)\n- Net: N+H + OH- → N + H2O\n\nThis is essentially a proton transfer / neutralization reaction."
